<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900430-0144</DOCNO><DOCID>900430-0144.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Judge Sentences   Stockbroker, Manager   To Prison for Fraud</HL><DATE>04/30/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9C</SO><IN>SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- A federal court judge here sentenced astockbroker and an investment manager to prison after theirconviction by a jury last month on 20 counts each ofsecurities, wire and bank fraud.   Gina Loren, 53 years old, was sentenced to six years inprison, followed by five years of probation. Daniel Burkhart,43, was sentenced to four years in prison, followed by fiveyears of probation, said James R. Asperger, an assistant U.S.attorney who prosecuted the case.</LP><TEXT>   The two convicts collected about $4.1 million from 44victims who were told that the funds would be held in a trustsecured by U.S. Treasury securities. Instead, the funds weredeposited -- and then withdrawn -- from an account at BatemanEichler, Hill Richards Inc. in Ventura, Calif., where Mr.Burkhart, who lives in Camarillo, Calif., was employed as astockbroker.   Ms. Loren, who resides in Los Angeles and is also known asGrace Horner, diverted large amounts of the funds to purchaseseveral luxury cars and a $1.6 million home in Orange, Calif.Mr. Burkhart received about $66,000 in payments over athree-month period for assisting Ms. Loren.   Officers at the brokerage firm alerted federal authoritieswhen they learned of the swindle, the U.S. attorney said. Thevictims included a group of Catholic nuns in South Dakota andretired military personnel.   Another participant in the scheme, Charles J. Lusin, 57,previously pleaded guilty to one felony count of mail fraudfor assisting Ms. Loren by preparing certain documents. Hewas sentenced March 26 to three years of probation and 300hours of community service.   In an interview Friday, Mr. Lusin said he also voluntarilygave up his license to practice law in California. He is nowunemployed and living in Temecula, Calif. An attorney for Mr.Burkhart declined to comment on behalf of his client. Ms.Loren and her attorney couldn't be reached.</TEXT></DOC>